Participant said he is currently scheduled to get his dog at the end of next year and he scheduled it this way because he has a knee surgery coming up and also would be retired by then, so he wouldn't have to take 6 weeks off from work to go pick up the dog. When asked if he wants to be contacted at a later date, he said the soonest he would be available to participate is probably this time next year. I told him that we completely understand and since part of the inclusion criteria is that he would need to be available to get his dog in the next three months, we will not move forward with recruitment at this time. He said to please keep him in mind for future studies.

Participant recently learned that their supervisor at work is not supportive of veterans with disabilities, so they are worried that having a service dog would create a stigma and possibly affect their performance reviews at their job. They said it's an unfortunate situation, but they need to work and can't take the risk at this time. They said they prefer to be removed from the recruitment list at this time, but would still like to receive the welcome packet in an email, just in case. JS also told them that if anything changes and they would like to move forward with participation, to reach out to our team and we are happy to help them get started at that time if we are still recruiting.
